### LINQ Methods in Detail

LINQ provides a comprehensive set of extension methods for querying data.

### Filtering (Where)

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 };

var evens = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0);
var evensWithIndex = numbers.Where((n, index) => n % 2 == 0 && index > 2);
```

### Projection (Select, SelectMany)

```csharp
var squares = numbers.Select(n => n * n);
var withIndex = numbers.Select((n, i) => new { Index = i, Value = n });

// Flatten nested collections
var words = new[] { "one two", "three four" };
var allWords = words.SelectMany(w => w.Split(' '));
// "one", "two", "three", "four"
```

### Sorting (OrderBy, ThenBy)

```csharp
var people = new[] { ("Alice", 30), ("Bob", 25), ("Charlie", 30) };

var sorted = people
    .OrderBy(p => p.Age)
    .ThenBy(p => p.Name)
    .ThenByDescending(p => p.Name.Length);
```

### Aggregation

```csharp
int[] nums = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };

int count = nums.Count();
int sum = nums.Sum();
double avg = nums.Average();
int min = nums.Min();
int max = nums.Max();
int product = nums.Aggregate((a, b) => a * b);  // 120
```

### Quantifiers

```csharp
bool allPositive = nums.All(n => n > 0);      // true
bool anyEven = nums.Any(n => n % 2 == 0);     // true
bool contains5 = nums.Contains(5);             // true
```

### Set Operations

```csharp
int[] set1 = { 1, 2, 3, 4 };
int[] set2 = { 3, 4, 5, 6 };

var distinct = set1.Distinct();
var union = set1.Union(set2);        // 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6
var intersect = set1.Intersect(set2); // 3, 4
var except = set1.Except(set2);       // 1, 2
```

### Partitioning

```csharp
int[] nums = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 };

var first3 = nums.Take(3);           // 1, 2, 3
var skip2 = nums.Skip(2);            // 3, 4, 5, 6
var whileLess5 = nums.TakeWhile(n => n < 5);  // 1, 2, 3, 4
var skipWhileLess3 = nums.SkipWhile(n => n < 3);  // 3, 4, 5, 6
```

### Element Operations

```csharp
int first = nums.First();              // 1
int last = nums.Last();                // 6
int firstMatch = nums.First(n => n > 3);  // 4
int? maybe = nums.FirstOrDefault(n => n > 10);  // null
int single = nums.Single(n => n == 5);  // 5 (throws if not exactly one)
int elementAt = nums.ElementAt(2);     // 3
```

### Grouping

```csharp
var people = new[] { ("Alice", "A"), ("Bob", "B"), ("Andy", "A") };

var grouped = people.GroupBy(p => p.Item2);
foreach (var group in grouped)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"{group.Key}: {group.Count()} people");
}
```

> **Key Point:** LINQ methods chain together for complex queries. Most methods use deferred execution. Methods like `ToList()`, `ToArray()`, `Count()`, `First()`, `Sum()` force immediate execution.

### Join Operations

```csharp
var orders = new[] { (1, "Alice"), (2, "Bob") };
var items = new[] { (1, "Laptop"), (1, "Mouse"), (2, "Keyboard") };

var query = orders.Join(items,
    o => o.Item1,  // orders key
    i => i.Item1,  // items key
    (o, i) => new { Customer = o.Item2, Item = i.Item2 });

